# "Run" means execute — not document

When the user says **run**, **execute**, **apply**, or **run it** (SQL, migration, schema, app, server), **you must perform the action in their environment**. Do not stop at adding a file to the repo or telling them to use a dashboard.

## Required actions by request type

| User says | You must |
|-----------|----------|
| Run this SQL / migration / schema | Execute on their Supabase project via **Supabase MCP** (`apply_migration` or `execute_sql`). Project id = ref from `VITE_SUPABASE_URL` in `.env` (e.g. `https://XXXX.supabase.co` → `XXXX`). |
| Run / restart / rebuild the app | Stop ports 3001/5173 + Electron, then `npm run electron:dev` from project root. Wait for Express on :3001. |
| Pull latest and run | `git fetch` + merge, `npm install` if deps changed, then rebuild/restart. Run any new `.sql` migrations on Supabase the same session. |

## Forbidden unless user explicitly opts out

- Adding `supabase/migrations/*.sql` only and saying "run this in the SQL Editor"
- "You need to apply this migration yourself"
- Assuming a file in the repo equals work done on the database

## Exceptions (honor explicit user words)

- "Pull only — do not build"
- "Don't run on Supabase yet"
- "Just show me the SQL"

## Supabase execution order

1. Read migration SQL from repo or user message.
2. Call `apply_migration` (DDL) or `execute_sql` (queries) on the correct `project_id`.
3. Confirm success (`list_tables` or a simple `SELECT` if needed).
4. Tell the user it is **done**, not pending.

## App execution order

See also `restart-app-after-changes.mdc` — stop first, then build + launch.
